se. </p>\n<p>So let&#8217;s do a little math, with a reminder that I&#8217;m not good at math. </p>\n<p>Using the handy date calculation tool from <a href=\"http://www.timeanddate.com/\" title=\"timeanddate.com\">Timeanddate.com</a>, from and including Thursday, December 11, 2008, to and including Friday, December 19, 2008, nine days have passed. The tool told me this equals:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>777,600 seconds (0.643 downloads a second)</li>\n<li>12,960 minutes (38.58 downloads per minute)</li>\n<li>216 hours (2,314.81 downloads per hour)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>That&#8217;s some serious bandwidth action. Go <a href=\"http://wordpress.org/download/\" title=\"Download WordPress 2.7\">download WordPress 2.7</a> now and let&#8217;s see how fast we can reach one million. By Monday? Wednesday? Anyone taking bets? <img src=\"http://s.wordpress.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_wink.gif\" alt=\";-)\" class=\"wp-smiley\" /> </p>\n<p>If it takes 0.64 seconds per download, how long before the WordPress 2.7 download counter will read one billion? Want to guess? Place more bets? </p>\n<p>I announced this on <a href=\"http://www.twitter.com/lorelleonwp/\" title=\"Lorelle on WordPress Twitter\">my Twitter</a> and <a href=\"http://www.webmaster-source.com/\" title=\"Webmaster Source\">Matt Harzewski (redwall_hp)</a> admitted that while he had upgraded many WordPress blogs to 2.7 since its release, he had only downloaded one copy. </p>\n<p>Have you been recycling your WordPress downloads? <img src=\"http://s.wordpress.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_biggrin.gif\" alt=\":D\" class=\"wp-smiley\" /> </p>\n<h4>Related Articles</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.blogherald.com/2008/12/10/wordpress-news-wordpress-27-released/\" title=\"WordPress 2.7 Released\">WordPress News: WordPress 2.7 Released</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://lorelle.wordpress.com/2008/12/18/wordpress-news-on-the-blog-herald/\" title=\"WordPress News on the Blog Herald\">WordPress News on the Blog Herald</a></li>\n<li><a 